Art,<br><br>
I'm afraid that I see the issue of atrocities in a different light.<br><br>
The title of this thread implies that there is evil in all of us. I do not dispute this. The Bible teaches as much in the parable of the adulterous woman. <br><br>
How prisoners are treated is a black and white issue.<br><br>
A friend sent me a copy of a MACV pamphlet that all of us received when we arrived in Vietnam. It is a guideline on treatment of prisoners. It is a bit lengthy. This is a summary.<br><br>
1. Handle him (the prisoner) firmly, promptly, but humanely.<br><br>
2. Take the captive quickly to security.<br><br>
3. Mistreatment of any captive is a criminal offense. Every soldier is personally responsible for the enemy in his hands.<br><br>
4. Treat the sick and wounded captive as best you can.<br>
   <br>
   The captive saved may be an intelligence source. In any case he is a human being and must be treated like one. The soldier who ignores the sick and wounded degrades his uniform.<br><br>
5. All persons in your hands, whether suspects, civilians, or combat captives, must be protected against violence, insults, curiosity, and reprisals of any kind.<br><br>
   Leave punishment to the courts and the judges. The soldier shows his strength by his fairness, firmness, and humanity to the persons in his hands.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>
When we harshly judge LT William Calley at My Lai, we are, in effect, saying that had we *personally* been there that day, we wouldn't have allowed such a thing to happen. Can we factor in all of the intangibles of the insanity of war and still arrive at this conclusion?<br><br>
How can we know?<br><br>
I sense a coming together of the people who were young during the time of the Vietnam War. I see an attempt to understand different viewpoints. <br><br>
Those who served in Vietnam only need to look at the code of conduct which I posted above to see the lost opportunities. <br><br>
On the subject of civilians, did we *really* embrace the Vietnamese. Did we, as *individual soldiers*, attempt to earnestly &quot;win the hearts and minds of the Vietnamese people&quot;? Did we conduct ourselves as &quot;guests of the people of South Vietnam&quot;? That was our mission wasn't it? Isn't that what our nation was led to believe - that we were in South Vietnam to fight for freedom?<br><br>
By taking responsibility I recognize that there were things that happened in Vietnam that needed to be protested in the streets of America.<br><br>
On the other hand, there are those who once judged *us* harshly. <br><br>
&quot;Baby Killer!&quot; <br><br>
No doubt, the years since Vietnam have taught *them* lessons. Maybe their excesses were of a different nature? Maybe their mistakes didn't result in the annihilation of a village or a family. But, I am willing to bet that the setbacks and failures in their personal lives revealed a previously unrecognized dark side. &quot;The Evil in All of Us&quot;. Surprise. <br><br>
Those who are sincere and conscientious realize that to put on the shoes of those who served in Vietnam is now a bit easier. The failures that the years provide humans show that maybe, just maybe, they would have gone along with the Calleys and those others who were weak in spirit. <br><br>
We, who served in Vietnam should offer no excuses, so that while bearing this burden we may tell others that,  &quot;the soldier shows his strength by his fairness, firmness, and humanity to the persons in his hands&quot;.<br><br>
In this way, only, can we prevail.<br><br>

